    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-11-08T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-11-08T02:00:00-05:00" n="612"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d612">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">794.00/11–852: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 612<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName corresp="#p_MRD1"
                            type="from">Murphy</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-11-08T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >November 8, 1952—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1496. During call on Prime Minister last night at his residence <persName
                        corresp="#p_YS1">Yoshida</persName> made following statements to <persName
                        corresp="#p_AJM1">Allison</persName> and me: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Japan intends to make some specific offer on reparations to
                            Philippines. Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_OK1"
                                >Okazaki</persName> will work out details. (Same statement made to
                                <persName corresp="#p_AJM1">Allison</persName> later in evening by
                            Wajima of Foreign Office who promised more details next week.)<note
                                n="1" xml:id="d612fn1">Further documentation on this particular
                                initiative is in file 294.9641 for late 1952 and early 1953. Japan
                                and the Philippines did not reach a reparations settlement until
                                1956.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>New Japanese Government will adhere to <persName corresp="#p_DJM1"
                                >Dodge</persName> line in fighting inflation. While <persName
                                corresp="#p_IH1">Ikeda</persName> no longer Finance Minister he
                            remains in Cabinet and according to <persName corresp="#p_YS1"
                                >Yoshida</persName> new Finance Minister has agreed.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Government will shortly establish information agency with primary
                            object of educating Japanese people in necessity of rearmament.
                                <persName corresp="#p_OT1">Ogata</persName>, Chief Secretary of
                                Cabinet<note n="2" xml:id="d612fn2">
                                <persName corresp="#p_OT1">Taketora Ogata</persName> held this post
                                Oct. 30–Nov. 29, 1952, after which he became Vice Premier until the
                                resignation of the last <persName corresp="#p_YS1"
                                    >Yoshida</persName> cabinet on Dec. 9, 1954.</note> is in charge
                            of making plans for this new organization.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Crown Prince will go to London via Canada for coronation of Queen
                            Elizabeth and it is hoped he can return via US and spend several weeks
                            in the US. This must be kept strictly confidential until formal approval
                            is received from Queen Elizabeth for Crown Prince to represent Emperor
                            at coronation.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>On the subject of rearmament <persName corresp="#p_YS1"
                                >Yoshida</persName> said that time is necessary to adjust public
                            opinion. As a result of the war great prejudices exist especially on the
                            part of Jap women against the military. <gloss target="#t_NPR1"
                                >NPR</gloss> had suffered because of these prejudices and that is
                            why it is necessary that the new national safety force appear to public
                            in favorable light. The public dreads the expense of a military
                            establishment. We said that as he knew Americans did not like the
                            expense either but Soviet aggression and expansionism left no
                            alternative.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Murphy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
